en support their child and make decisions for him. Unfortunately, in my work, in practice, I see that, unfortunately, this situation is still different, that all parents either do not know how or for some reason do not want to deal with their child's problem, if he perhaps lacks the necessary skills, needs help himself, or even has himself as the cause of his child's problems. The topic has been discussed six times in the social committee of the Riigikogu. Various aspects of the problem have been explained by specialists in the field. Representatives of thirty-six organizations also signed a joint appeal, which justifies the importance of the amendment to the law. It has been a year and a half since the chancellor of justice drew the country's attention to the fact that this small change in the law would be fair and necessary for young people. Today we are in a situation where the social committee of the Riigikogu has been processing this issue for almost a year, including the Ministry of Education, the Ministry of Justice, the Ministry of Social Affairs, including the Prime Minister and the Minister of Social Affairs, who have expressed their support for this small change in the law. And we still process and cannot process him. What at first seemed like a small and simple change in the law has grown into a fundamental confrontation. EKRE member Urmas Espenberg, who is part of the social committee, says that in theory they agree that young people could, in exceptional cases, have access to a psychiatrist's talk without a parent's permission. In practice, no agreement is reached. According to Espenberg, the two exceptional cases in which a young person could turn to a psychiatrist without a parent are the absence of a guardian and domestic violence. I certainly don't agree with the fact that everyone starts visiting psychiatrists on their own, so that any child should go to a psychologist for counseling first, then the psychologist will see what to do next. So what are the opponents of the changes in the law afraid of, whether they don't trust young people or they don't trust specialists in the field, i.e. psychiatrists? Espenberg cites as the main reasons for the need to work with the family the fear that too strong drugs will be prescribed to young people. But also the fear that mental problems will become a fashionable disease or that young people will start selling prescribed drugs on the black market. After all, young people are prone to trying all kinds of things, and when the story starts that they can all work, then the story of antidepressants remains open. Then maybe they start selling it to each other. Psychiatrist dismisses fears of opponents of law changes. It is the duty and competence of the doctor to assess the patient's condition and act accordingly. It is always the doctor's wisdom to see through these situations, to see what motives actually come and how this drug use is, perhaps that there are rules for this, by following which we can prevent most of these problems. According to both specialists and youth workers, the problem is serious and requires action. I approached thirteen youth workers from four different institutions dealing with young people, and a third of them have actually had contact with the issue of where a child needs psychiatric help, but due to the parent's opposition, it has not been found. I also ask them for stories. The stories are scary sometimes, to say the least. Two of these stories led to suicide attempts, fortunately unsuccessful attempts, one of which is an ongoing process where the child then does not dare to contact his parents, as his parents are very strongly of the belief that mental health issues are something that only the insane or severely mentally ill deal with. Urmas Espenberg proposes a solution that another adult in contact with young people could issue a referral or permission to a psychiatrist. In practice, it looks like this: we have all kinds of networks, there is a youth and child protection network, then it is the same police where certain cases are registered, they can immediately make a referral there, then there are school psychologists who you can turn to. There are many of these possibilities, there are many psychologists in Estonia and they are all relatively untapped. So that we should think about solving these things somehow and not blaming each other here. However, each intermediate step increases the bureaucracy and requires additional forces. At the moment, the problem is to fulfill the existing requirements. Only thirty-nine percent of Estonian schools have a psychologist at work. This means that more than half of the schools have to manage without a psychologist. Where they are, they are very good, and where they are not, they are sorely lacking. What happens if a person does not get help in time? Well, in the case of mental disorders, one of the most common of which is, for example, depression, there is a very high risk that it will become chronic. But before it becomes chronic, it spoils your quality of life, i.e. the young person cannot learn, cannot communicate, realize himself in his life. And he deviates from everyday life, that is, they go home, sit at the computer at first, soon not there anymore, lie down in bed, eat at best. They are completely hopeless and think only that the only solution would be to die. The number of people infected with the coronavirus exceeded two hundred people on several days this week, and Social Affairs Minister Tanel Kiik said on Friday that due to the spread of the coronavirus, Estonia is on the way to a healthcare crisis. Hanneli Rudi investigated how the virus is currently spreading. Two hundred eight, one hundred thirty one, two hundred forty one. These are not winning points in some game of darts, but the number of people infected with the coronavirus this week. Kind of a sad record. However, even in mid-October, Estonia stood out in Europe for its exceptionally low 